<div id="review_496667095" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/496667095" />
    <a title="Beverly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4509739-beverly"><img alt="Beverly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1289105432p2/4509739.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/496667095?book_show_action=true">Jan 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beverly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beverly" href="/user/show/4509739-beverly">Beverly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer496667095" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7957001667939082704">Leon Uris now gives us the story of the birth of the state of Israel from the Arab point of view. His point of view could be categorized as anti-Arab, so everything he writes needs to be taken with a grain of salt. He follows one family as they cope with the changing times. Haj Ibrahim is the muktar of his village which is situated on the road to Jerusalem in a very strategic spot. Right down the road, on land that used to belong to the same absentee landlord that owns Ibrahim&apos;s village, a new J</span>
  <span id="freeText7957001667939082704" style="display:none">Leon Uris now gives us the story of the birth of the state of Israel from the Arab point of view. His point of view could be categorized as anti-Arab, so everything he writes needs to be taken with a grain of salt. He follows one family as they cope with the changing times. Haj Ibrahim is the muktar of his village which is situated on the road to Jerusalem in a very strategic spot. Right down the road, on land that used to belong to the same absentee landlord that owns Ibrahim's village, a new Jewish Kibbutz is built. The Haj forms a friendship with the Haganah liasion, Gideon Asch. They become good friends and Ibrahim feels that he is really the only person he can trust. All the Arabs are characterized as being untrustworthy, lazy, scheming, harsh, and embedded in tradition. If they lose a battle, they report that it was a training exercise, testing the Jewish response. They blame everything on the Jews, even when it was an Arab's fault. They are undisciplined and easily manipulated. Their so-called leaders ask thousands of Arabs to leave their homes for strategic reasons. All these people wind up in refugee camps which have no organization whatsoever. Haj Ibrahim and his family wind up in a camp outside Jericho. He becomes a very respected man voicing opposition to the Arab leaders. He is the voice of reason but no one listens to him. This story is very relevant today. It shows how things started to unravel, leading to the current situation in the Middle East. The Arabs have raised generations to hate the infidel whether they are Jewish or other non-believers. It was a hard book to read because they could have lived peacefully side by side with the Jews. Many Arabs chose to stay and their lives have been better. Those that left, were given many choices. They were offered the opportunity to return but they chose not to. They were offered the materials and expertise to build schools, industries, crops, but they chose not to accept. They continue to blame the Jews for all their hardships. It is very sad.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7957001667939082704" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


