<div id="review_1872329565" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1872329565" />
    <a title="A Man Called Ove" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8676317-a-man-called-ove"><img alt="A Man Called Ove" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1333976381p2/8676317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1872329565?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="A Man Called Ove" class="user" itemprop="url" name="A Man Called Ove" href="/user/show/8676317-a-man-called-ove">A Man Called Ove</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8676317-a-man-called-ove?shelf=world-history-20th-cent">world-history-20th-cent</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1872329565" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13536479762068065559">3.5/5 The book presents the Arab viewpoint of the Israel-Palestine partition in 1948 and does so with courage, candidness, passion and empathy. &quot;The Haj&quot; in the title refers to &quot;Haj Ibrahim&quot; the book&apos;s central character, a tribal leader and not the religious pilgrimage.<br/>The book is divided into 5 sections - a) Arab life in Palestine in the 1930s and early 1940s, b) the dispute, war and partition, c) the exile n terrible condition of refugees, d) the attempt to resettle refugees and work for peace</span>
  <span id="freeText13536479762068065559" style="display:none">3.5/5 The book presents the Arab viewpoint of the Israel-Palestine partition in 1948 and does so with courage, candidness, passion and empathy. "The Haj" in the title refers to "Haj Ibrahim" the book's central character, a tribal leader and not the religious pilgrimage.<br />The book is divided into 5 sections - a) Arab life in Palestine in the 1930s and early 1940s, b) the dispute, war and partition, c) the exile n terrible condition of refugees, d) the attempt to resettle refugees and work for peace and e) the aftermath till d early 1950s.<br />A few yrs ago, I loved the author's "Exodus" on the birth of Israel and I picked this one up soon after to read d Arab version of events. But I abandoned "The Haj" after 100 pages as I thought it was biased. However, now, having read a lot on the region and religion, think Uris has nailed it. There r powerful scenes in the book which show a mirror to the Arab society. The book is a must-read !<br />And I couldnt help drawing parallels with Kashmir and Pakistan who cant let go of hatred of non-Muslims.<br />As Golda Meir, Israeli ex-PM said<br />"There will be peace when they love their children more than they hate us." After all, why didnt Kashmiri Pandits pick up guns against the Kashmiri Muslims who exiled them?<br />Or as the hounding of d Dangal movie's child star Zaira Wasim recently makes me think<br />"There will be peace when they love their children more than their religion."<br />Fittingly the book ends with the central character "Haj Ibrahim" murdering his adult, mature daughter for losing her virginity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13536479762068065559" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

